# Command /get-rules

**Triggered when the user types `/get-rules`.**

Scans the current project, detects technologies, then lists and optionally imports
applicable rules from `C:\opt\src\CursorRulesLibrary\Library`.

## Step 1 — Detect Technologies

Scan the project root and subfolders for the following signals:

| Signal | Detected technology |
|--------|---------------------|
| `*.csproj` exists | C# project |
| `.csproj` contains `Microsoft.AspNetCore` | → **CSharp-WebApp** |
| `.csproj` contains `<UseWPF>true` | → **WPF** |
| `.csproj` contains `IBM.Data.Db2` or `Net.IBM.Data.Db2` or `Dedge.DedgeCommon` | → **Db2** |
| `.csproj` contains `NLog` | → **Logging** |
| `.csproj` contains `Serilog` | → **Logging** |
| `.csproj` contains `DedgeAuth` (any package or project ref) | → **DedgeAuth** |
| `.csproj` present but none of the above web/WPF signals | → **CSharp-WinApp** |
| `*.ps1` files exist | → **PowerShell** |
| `*.wxs` or `*.wixproj` files exist | → **Installer** |
| `*.html` or `*.css` or `*.js` files exist (not in publish/node_modules) | → **Web-UI** |
| UNC paths (`\\server\`) referenced in any source file | → **Server** |
| `*.Tests.csproj` or `*Test*.csproj` exists | → **Testing** |
| `.cursor/rules/command-*.mdc` files exist | → **Commands** |

**Always include these themes regardless of signals:**

- **Agent** — universal agent behaviour rules
- **Git** — every project uses git
- **Documentation** — every project needs doc standards

## Step 2 — Build Candidate Rule List

For each detected theme, list all `.mdc` files under
`C:\opt\src\CursorRulesLibrary\Library\<Theme>\`.

Use PowerShell to collect them:

```powershell
$libraryRoot = "C:\opt\src\CursorRulesLibrary\Library"
$themes = @("Agent", "Git", "Documentation") # + detected themes
$candidates = $themes | ForEach-Object {
    Get-ChildItem "$libraryRoot\$_\*.mdc" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
}
```

## Step 3 — Compare with Existing Project Rules

```powershell
$existing = (Get-ChildItem ".cursor\rules\*.mdc").Name
$candidates | ForEach-Object {
    $status = if ($existing -contains $_.Name) { "HAVE" } else { "MISSING" }
    [PSCustomObject]@{ Status = $status; Theme = $_.Directory.Name; File = $_.Name }
}
```

## Step 4 — Report to User

Present a markdown table:

| Status | Theme | Rule file | Action |
|--------|-------|-----------|--------|
| ✅ HAVE | Git | git-standards.mdc | — |
| ❌ MISSING | Logging | logging-nlog.mdc | *import?* |

Then ask: **"Import all missing rules? (yes / pick individual names)"**

## Step 5 — Import Selected Rules

For each rule the user confirms, copy from Library to `.cursor/rules/`:

```powershell
Copy-Item "$libraryRoot\<Theme>\<rule>.mdc" ".cursor\rules\<rule>.mdc" -Force
```

- Do **not** overwrite an existing rule without asking first if the content differs.
- After copying, read and summarize what each imported rule does in one line.

## Step 6 — Commit the imported rules (optional)

If any rules were imported, offer to commit:

```powershell
git add ".cursor\rules\"
git commit -m "chore(rules): import applicable rules from CursorRulesLibrary" `
           -m "Imported: <list of rule filenames>"
git push
```

